docs.abstract: Mary McLeod Bethune is the first Black American to be represented with a state statue in the National Statuary Hall. Her likeness replaces a statue honoring one of the last Confederate generals to surrender.

docs.lead_paragraph: Mary McLeod Bethune on Wednesday became the first Black American to be represented with a state statue in National Statuary Hall, a central room of the United States Capitol, honored for her work championing education and civil rights.

docs.abstract: Alex Lasry, son of a majority owner of the Milwaukee Bucks, learned there’s a difference between making fans happy and appealing to voters.
docs.snippet: Alex Lasry, son of a majority owner of the Milwaukee Bucks, learned there’s a difference between making fans happy and appealing to voters.
docs.lead_paragraph: MILWAUKEE — When Alex Lasry dropped out of the Democratic primary for Senate in Wisconsin on Wednesday, he said “there was no path to victory,” something no owner of a sports franchise ever wants to admit. He said he had concluded he could not beat Lt. Gov. Mandela Barnes and urged voters to rally behind Barnes to defeat the Republican incumbent, Senator Ron Johnson, in November.

headline.main: It’s a Long Leap From Sports Team Owner to U.S. Senator
headline.print_headline: A Sports Team Owner Learns It’s Easier to Please Fans Than Win Voters

docs.lead_paragraph: In America, to vote in a federal election is to commit a secret act. One votes in private, in a curtained booth, on intimate terms with an oversize ballot. But little in American public life stays private for long.

docs.abstract: Boston’s new police commissioner, Michael Cox, was the victim of an assault by fellow officers who mistook him for a suspect.
docs.snippet: Boston’s new police commissioner, Michael Cox, was the victim of an assault by fellow officers who mistook him for a suspect.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOSTON — Before dawn on a January morning in 1995, the phone rang in the home of Michael A. Cox Sr., a Boston police officer. His wife answered, still groggy. He had been hurt. As two of his fellow officers rushed her to the emergency room, she asked what had happened.

headline.main: He Fought Boston’s Blue Wall of Silence. Now He’s the Commissioner.

docs.abstract: North Carolina holds an illuminating — and alarming — political mirror up to the country.
docs.snippet: North Carolina holds an illuminating — and alarming — political mirror up to the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: CLAYTON, N.C. — For a tidy snapshot of our messy country, you could do worse than North Carolina’s newly redrawn 13th Congressional District, where suburb yields to exurb and fields of tobacco and sweet potatoes somehow hold their ground. I had to drive only 15 miles of it to see two versions of America — and to see them at war.

headline.main: One of America’s Most Seductive States Is Also One of Its Scariest
headline.print_headline: North Carolina Is Both Seductive and Scary
